    "body": "Hello and thank you for you great work :)\n\n### Problem\n\nOn Windows, `jobstart()` sometimes does not call `on_exit` for a GUI executable that exits after a runtime crash/assertion.\n\nThe process is gone from Task Manager, but Neovim does not seem to deliver the job exit callback. Plugins that rely on `jobstart()` lifecycle tracking, like overseer.nvim, keep showing the task as still running.\n\nThis looks like the job id becomes invalid without `on_exit` being delivered. I am not sure whether the root cause is Neovim, libuv, or something Windows-specific.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nStart a Windows GUI executable with `jobstart()`:\n\n```lua\nlocal job_id = vim.fn.jobstart({\n  \"C:/path/to/app.exe\",\n}, {\n  cwd = \"C:/path/to\",\n  stdout_buffered = true,\n  stderr_buffered = true,\n  on_exit = function(_, code, event)\n    vim.schedule(function()\n      vim.print({ code = code, event = event })\n    end)\n  end,\n})\n```\n\nIn my case the executable is an Odin Windows GUI app. The GUI appears correctly when launched through `jobstart()`.\n\nIf the app exits normally, `on_exit` works.\n\nIf the app hits an Odin runtime assertion/trap and exits, the process disappears from Task Manager, but `on_exit` is not called.\n\nAfter that, checking the job can return:\n\n```lua\nvim.fn.jobwait({ job_id }, 0)\n-- { -3 }\n```\n\nSo Neovim appears to consider the job id invalid, but the exit callback was never delivered.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIf the child process exits for any reason, `jobstart()` should call `on_exit` exactly once.\n\nIdeally it should report the real Windows exit code. If that is not possible, it should still notify that the job ended instead of silently invalidating the job id.\n\n### Extra notes\n\n`vim.system()` appears to detect the exit/crash more reliably in my testing, but it is not a good replacement here because it does not launch/show this Windows GUI app the same way `jobstart()` does.\n\nSo this seems related to the `jobstart()` process lifecycle path specifically.\n\n### Nvim version\n\nNVIM v0.12.0\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 10 22H2 / 10.0.19045\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nNeovide GUI client, not running inside a terminal.\n\nThanks for helping!",
